&quot;Dialogue Outside Con Thien&quot;<br><br>
A poem by Robert H. Dirr Jr.<br><br>
While walking a path through tangles of mongrel<br>
     shrub and coagulated wait-a-minute vines,<br>
Oliver held up a finger, sprinkled with scratches<br>
     and cuts and dried blood and pointed to<br>
A delicate red plant.  It forced its way through<br>
     the cracks between three trees and thrived.<br>
&quot;It's the only pretty thing I've seen in this jungle<br>
     and even IT'S got fuckin' thorns all over it.&quot;<br><br>
We filed by and pondered the significance of<br>
     such an elegant flower flourishing,<br>
Surrounded by craters and booby traps and<br>
     black trees with Agent-Orange leaves.<br>
Seargeant Jackson bent over to get a closer look<br>
     at it and broke the stem with his heel.<br>
&quot;What the fuck are you lookin' at?  It's gonna<br>
     die anyway, like everything else.&quot;<br><br>
Doc saw the disfigured plant and got on his knees<br>
     and opened the first aid kit so he<br>
Could make a splint with two tongue depressors<br>
     and some white surgical tape.<br>
He fixed the sagging flower and thought of high<br>
     school days and Gertrude Stein:<br>
&quot;A rose is a rose is a rose...<br>
     You are what you are what you are...<br>
          Peace, brother.&quot;<br>

